<br>
The problem is in the mentality of most computer users. A lot of people are like “I don’t understand that it must be bad!” “That’s different I don’t like it” and that is the wrong attitude. Unfortunately, it is essentially due to the way that a lot of people in our society perceive the world (homosexuality and racism are prime examples). People also need to have more patience (which doesn't occur too often here in Britain).<br>
<br>
It isn’t just the user that is at fault though, it is also a problem created (in quite a large proportion) by the developer. A lot of frequent Linux users and developers look down on users of others Operating Systems. They see themselves as elite enough to use and create a complex OS effectively and as it took them so much time and effort they don’t like to help others. Most will respond with a “rtfm“ (read the fucking manual) or “if you don’t have the knowledge to use a search engine then you won’t understand Linux”. This is again very wrong and makes it so hard to receive support for Linux.<br>
<br>
This is partly why there aren’t as many applications and games for Linux because people have this mentality. The press, business, governments, they all support the large capitalist corporations such as Microsoft, IBM etc. because they provide them with more money than the others. Freedom, open source, and the essentially socialist corporations are viewed with a bitter hatred and aren’t promoted for that very reason. Did you know it is illegal to wear clothing that indicates blasphemous acts? This is exactly what I am talking about, the governments and corporations pick and choose what should and should not be used. Bah, I am going off topic… will leave that for another day.<br>
<br>
Don’t get me wrong, Microsoft has done a lot for the industry but they have also started to close it off to their way of thinking and this must stop! There are so many different avenues you can travel down and I think that everyone should start to be more open-minded and liberal.<br>
<br>
The new middleware (platform independent software e.g. games libraries, basically DirectX for all systems including games consoles) will hopefully put an end to the gaming barrier at least. Hopefully more will follow! God I could go on and on…. LOL<br>
<br>
Sometimes using more than one OS on a PC can be an advantage. In my case the amount of apps I use just bog down Win9x/Me and they end up acting so erratically it isn't worth using them. This is why I use Win Me for gaming and multimedia only as they are essentially designed with gaming and word processing etc. in mind. I also use Win 2000 (on the same computer) for development, Internet access and most other things. It is far more stable and secure and was built for business and development not gaming.<br>
<br>
I also use Linux Mandrake 8.2 for similar reasons to Win 2000 but also because it is just so much better for development, it provides so much more choice and is easier to configure for certain environments such as Perl. Not to mention the fact most applications are platform independent and more stable due to the open source initiative. The numbers of apps that are provided exceed those available to Windows tenfold. The only difference is in compatibility, games and support (in both the end-user sense and for hardware e.g. drivers), which is the fault of the companies that hold a monopoly over the industry e.g. USB is supported in Linux, however a lot of the devices that use USB aren't. Most of the developers just say “Linux isn’t used enough for us to bother making a device driver for it”.<br>
<br>
I occasionally use FreeBSD 4.5 also (BSD = Berkley Systems Development, a cross between UNIX and Linux created by Berkley University) which is extremely secure. I will be using that to host my websites and various other services such as IRC once I get ADSL.<br>
<br>
Obviously if you like Microsoft, you are happy with the OS you are using and it does everything you need with minimal error occurrences then stick with that. Not everyone needs or has to use a different Operating System but the choice and awareness should be there at least e.g. What do all PC's at Comet, Dixons and other highstreet stores come installed with? Do you here a mention of any other OS?<br>
<br>
Cheers<br>
<br>
